"Lo M.-H., Famiglietti J.S.","Precipitation response to land subsurface hydrologic processes in atmospheric general circulation model simulations",2011,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","116","5", D05107,"","",,,10.1029/2010JD015134,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79952470257&partnerID=40&md5=18c438d73e9e85e1fcae4af763eb1f18","Department of Earth System Science, University of California, Irvine, CA 92697, United States; UC Center for Hydrologic Modeling, University of California, Irvine, CA, United States","Lo, M.-H., Department of Earth System Science, University of California, Irvine, CA 92697, United States, UC Center for Hydrologic Modeling, University of California, Irvine, CA, United States; Famiglietti, J.S., Department of Earth System Science, University of California, Irvine, CA 92697, United States, UC Center for Hydrologic Modeling, University of California, Irvine, CA, United States","Several studies have established that soil moisture increases after adding a groundwater component in land surface models, owing to the additional supply of subsurface water. However, the impact of groundwater on the spatial-temporal variability of precipitation has received little attention. This study explores how a groundwater representation in land surface models alters precipitation distributions through coupled groundwater-land-atmosphere simulations. Results indicate that the addition of groundwater yields a global increase in soil water content and evapotranspiration, a decrease in surface air temperature, and an increase in cloud cover fraction. These result in globally inhomogeneous changes in precipitation. In the boreal summer, tropical land regions show a positive anomaly in the Northern Hemisphere and a negative anomaly in the Southern Hemisphere. As a result, an asymmetric dipole is found over tropical land regions along the equator. Furthermore, in the transition climatic zone where the land and atmosphere are strongly coupled, precipitation also increases. Two main mechanisms are suggested for the two different regions with increased precipitation. The ""rich-get-richer"" mechanism is responsible for the positive precipitation anomalies over the tropical land regions, while a positive feedback of land-atmosphere interaction is the major contributor to increased precipitation over central North America. This study highlights the importance of land subsurface hydrologic processes in the climate system and has further implications for global water cycle dynamics. Copyright 2011 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Earth atmosphere; Feedback; Geologic models; Groundwater; Soil moisture; Surface measurement; Tropics; Water content; Water supply; Atmospheric general circulation models; Climate system; Climatic zone; Cloud cover; Global water cycle; Hydrologic process; Land surface models; Northern Hemispheres; Positive feedback; Precipitation anomalies; Precipitation distribution; Soil water content; Southern Hemisphere; Spatial temporals; Subsurface waters; Surface air temperatures; Tropical lands; Computer simulation; air temperature; atmospheric general circulation model; cloud cover; evapotranspiration; groundwater; hydrological cycle; hydrological response; land surface; Northern Hemisphere; precipitation (climatology); soil moisture; soil water; Southern Hemisphere; spatiotemporal analysis; water content; water yield; North America",,,,,,"Amenu, G.G., Kumar, P., Liang, X.-Z., Interannual variability of deep-layer hydrologic memory and mechanisms of its influence on surface energy fluxes (2005) Journal of Climate, 18 (23), pp. 5024-5045. , DOI 10.1175/JCLI3590.1; Anyah, R.O., Weaver, C.P., Miguez-Macho, G., Fan, Y., Robock, A., Incorporating water table dynamics in climate modeling: 3. Simulated groundwater influence on coupled land-atmosphere variability (2008) J. Geophys. Res., 113, pp. D07103. , doi:10.1029/2007JD009087; Beven, K.J., Kirkby, M.J., Physically based, variable contribut